                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="197.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Thermodynamics is the study of heat, energy, and the processes that involve their transformation. Temperature measures how hot or cold an object is, while heat is the energy transferred between objects due to temperature differences. When a hot object touches a cold one, energy flows from the hotter to the colder object until thermal equilibrium is reached. This exchange can occur through conduction, convection, or radiation." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="314.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="The laws of thermodynamics govern these processes. The First Law states that energy cannot be created or destroyed; it can only be transferred or transformed (also known as the conservation of energy). The Second Law introduces the concept of entropy, explaining that systems naturally progress toward disorder and that some energy is always lost as heat. Thermodynamics plays a critical role in engines, refrigerators, and even in understanding climate systems and biological processes." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Label layoutX="30.0" layoutY="414.0" prefHeight="53.0" prefWidth="686.0" text="Quantum Physics (Intro)">
