                        <Font name="Segoe UI Semibold" size="25.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="486.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Quantum physics is the branch of physics that deals with the behavior of matter and energy at very small scales; it is typically at the level of atoms and subatomic particles. Unlike classical physics, which predicts deterministic outcomes, quantum mechanics introduces probabilities. One of the key experiments that sparked quantum theory is the photoelectric effect, where light shining on a metal surface ejects electrons. This demonstrated that light can act as particles called photons." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="603.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Other strange and fascinating ideas in quantum physics include wave-particle duality, where particles like electrons exhibit both wave and particle behavior, and Heisenbergâ€™s Uncertainty Principle, which states that certain properties (like position and momentum) cannot both be precisely known at the same time. While these ideas seem abstract, they underpin technologies like semiconductors, lasers, and quantum computing." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Label layoutX="30.0" layoutY="704.0" prefHeight="53.0" prefWidth="686.0" text="Nuclear Physics">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI Semibold" size="25.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="776.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Nuclear physics focuses on the nucleus of the atom and the interactions within it. It explains phenomena such as radioactivity, where unstable atomic nuclei emit radiation to become more stable. This radiation can take the form of alpha particles, beta particles, or gamma rays. Understanding these processes is essential for nuclear medicine, energy production, and radiological safety." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Text layoutX="30.0" layoutY="876.0" strokeType="OUTSIDE" strokeWidth="0.0" text="Nuclear fission is the process of splitting a heavy nucleus (like uranium) into lighter nuclei, releasing a large amount of energy. This is the principle behind nuclear power plants and atomic bombs. Nuclear fusion, on the other hand, combines light nuclei (like hydrogen) into heavier ones, also releasing energy. This is the process that powers the sun. While fusion is not yet a practical energy source on Earth, it holds promise for the future of clean and sustainable energy." textAlignment="JUSTIFY" wrappingWidth="727.7760620117188">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Segoe UI" size="16.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Text>
                  <Label layoutX="27.0" layoutY="974.0" prefHeight="53.0" prefWidth="686.0" text="Physics in Technology and Environment">
